The paper proposes a generative model for learning the underlying structure of 3D shapes, which involves computer vision (CV) and machine learning (LG) techniques. The model uses skip-connections, which are commonly used in deep learning for image processing (CV), and can infer a hierarchical representation of objects. The paper also discusses the use of probabilistic manifolds, which is a common concept in artificial intelligence (AI). Finally, the paper evaluates the model's performance on tasks such as 3D model retrieval, which involves natural language processing (CL), and compares it to state-of-the-art alternatives, which is a common practice in graphics (GR) research. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.CV and cs.LG, followed by cs.GR, cs.AI, and cs.CL.
